{{Infobox radio station | name = DR P1 | image = DR_P1_logo_2015.png | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = | city = | area = [[Denmark]] | branding = | slogan = | frequency = | translator = | repeater = | airdate = {{Start date and age|1925|}} | last airdate = <!-- for defunct stations --> | share = | share as of = | share source = | format = | language = [[Danish language|Danish]] | power = | erp = | haat = | class = | facility_id = | coordinates = | callsign_meaning = | former_callsigns = | former_frequencies = | affiliations = | operator = [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] | owner = [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] | licensee = | sister_stations = | webcast = *[https://www.dr.dk/radio/live/p1/ Web Stream] '''HTTP progressive Streams''' *[http://live-icy.gss.dr.dk/A/A03L.mp3.m3u (Shoutcast, 92 Kbps MP3)] *[http://live-icy.gss.dr.dk/A/A03H.mp3.m3u (Shoutcast, 192 Kbps MP3)] '''HLS Streams''' *[http://drradio1-lh.akamaihd.net/i/p1_9@143503/master.m3u8 (192 Kbps AAC)] | website = {{URL|https://www.dr.dk/p1}} }} '''DR P1''' ‚Äì in Denmark normally referred to as simply '''P1''' ‚Äì is a Danish [[radio broadcasting|radio station]] operated by the [[DR (broadcaster)|Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]. P1 has evolved into a pure voice channel with a focus on news, documentaries, political debates, education, general cultural, scientific and social programming.
Since 1 November 2011 P1 has had to share its nationwide FM channel frequencies with [[DR P2|P2]] since DR lost the rights to continue the use of the fourth nationwide FM channel which P2 had been using.<ref>{{cite news|title=P2 flytter ind hos P1 p√• FM|url=https://www.dr.dk/presse/p2-flytter-ind-hos-p1-paa-fm|accessdate=6 April 2017|publisher=DR|date=6 October 2011}}</ref> P1 broadcats on the FM channel during daytime. Both channels continued as two separate channels digitally on [[Digital audio broadcasting|DAB]] and [[Internet radio|online]].<ref>{{cite news|title=P1 og P2 forts√¶tter som digital radio|url=http://www.dr.dk/Temaer/digitalradio/artikler/20120305204950.htm|accessdate=6 April 2017|publisher=DR|date=9 March 2015}}</ref>
==History== The station was established in 1925 with the start of operations of '''Statsradiofonien'''. In 1959 Statsradiofonien changed its name to '''Danmarks Radio''', and to '''DR''' in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|title=TIDSLINJE: Fra Statsradiofonien til DR|url=http://www.billedbladet.dk/kendte/danmark/tv/dr/tidslinje-fra-statsradiofonien-til-dr|website=Billedbladet.dk|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>
Since 1931 the station has had its own identifying pause signal and chime called ''Dr√∏mte mig en dr√∏m i nat''<ref>{{cite news|title=DRs pausesignal har v√¶ret i √¶teren i 80 √•r|url=https://www.dr.dk/presse/drs-pausesignal-har-vaeret-i-aeteren-i-80-aar|accessdate=6 April 2017|publisher=DR|date=23 August 2011}}</ref> which has been modernized several times since, most recently by [[Thomas Blachman]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blachman st√•r bag P1's nye lyd|url=http://politiken.dk/kultur/medier/art4845179/Blachman-st%C3%A5r-bag-P1s-nye-lyd|accessdate=6 April 2017|publisher=Politiken|date=9 April 2010}}</ref>
In January 2004 P1 started 24-hour broadcasting,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jensen|first1=Karsten|title=Taleradio 24 timer i d√∏gnet med ny P1 Nat|url=http://www.radionytarkiv.dk/artikel/default.asp?id=8895|accessdate=6 April 2017|date=12 January 2004}}</ref> whereas earlier it rebroadcast [[DR P3]] programming from midnight until 6 a.m.
On 1 October 2017 P1 became available on [[Digital_audio_broadcasting#DAB.2B_2|DAB+]] radio when a nationwide switch-over took place.<ref>{{cite news|title=Overgangen til DAB+ udsat til 1. oktober 2017|url=http://danskemedier.dk/nyhed/overgangen-til-dab-udsat-til-1-oktober-2017/|accessdate=8 April 2017|agency=Danske Medier|date=18 May 2016}}</ref>
