'''Domestic analogy''' is an international affairs term coined by Professor [[Hedley Bull]].<ref name = "Bull">"Society and Anarchy in international Relations" and "The Grotian Conception of International Society" in {{cite book | last =Butterfield | first =Herbert | authorlink = |author2=Martin Wright | year =1968 | title =Diplomatic Investigations: Essays in the Theory of International Politics | publisher =Harvard University Press | location = | isbn = 0-674-21001-8 }}</ref> Domestic analogy is the idea that states are like a "society of individuals". The [[analogy]] makes the presumption that relations between individuals and relations between states are the same.<ref name = "ency">{{cite web | title =Political Realism | work = The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy | url =http://www.iep.utm.edu/p/polreal.htm | accessdate=2006-09-05 }}</ref> The domestic analogy is used when aggression is explained as the international equivalent of armed robbery or murder. A person can look at international affairs like a society of people, except there is no police, and every conflict threatens the structure as a whole with collapse.<ref name = "wal">{{cite book | last =Walzer | first =Michael | authorlink =Michael Walzer | year =1977 | title =Just and Unjust Wars | publisher =Basic Books | location = | isbn =0-465-03705-4 }} p. 58-59</ref>
In his famous book ''[[Just and Unjust Wars]]'', [[Michael Walzer]] uses the term to explain what is a just and unjust war.<ref name = "wal" />
==Notes== {{refbegin}} {{refend}} {{reflist}}
==Further reading== *{{cite book | last =Suganami | first =Hidemi | authorlink = | year =1989 | title =The Domestic Analogy and World Order Proposals | publisher =Cambridge University Press | location = | isbn =0-521-34341-0 }}
*{{cite book | last =Rolf | first =Jan Niklas | authorlink = | year =2014 | title =The State of Nature Analogy in International Relations Theory | publisher =International Relations 28(2): 159-192 | location = | isbn = }} [[Category:International relations]]
