{{about|the agreement signed in 1975|the peace accord signed in 2012|Nakuru County Peace Accord}}
The '''Nakuru Agreement''', signed on June 21, 1975, in [[Nakuru]], [[Kenya]], was an attempt to salvage the [[Alvor Agreement]], which granted [[Angola]] independence from [[Portugal]] and established a transitional government. While the Nakuru Agreement did produce a truce between the three nationalist movements‚Äîthe [[Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola]] (MPLA), [[National Liberation Front of Angola]] (FNLA), and [[National Union for the Total Independence of Angola]] (UNITA)‚Äîit was a fragile truce that dissolved on July 9, 1975.<ref name="hopkins">McDannald, Alexander Hopkins. ''The Americana Annual: An Encyclopedia of Current Events'', 1976. Page 86.</ref>
==Negotiation== The three principal separatist leaders, MPLA's [[Agostinho Neto]], UNITA's [[Jonas Savimbi]], and the FNLA's [[Holden Roberto]] met in Nakuru from June 15-21. [[Kenyan President]] [[Jomo Kenyatta]] moderated the negotiations. The leaders "denounce[d] the use of force as a means of solving problems" and again agreed to put down their arms and disarm civilians.<ref name=wright>{{cite book|last1=Wright|first1=George|title=The Destruction of a Nation: United States' Policy Towards Angola Since 1945|date=1997|publisher=Pluto Press|isbn=9780745310299|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Destruction_of_a_Nation.html?id=cINUCik7OeUC|pages=60‚Äì61}}</ref>
